To solve this, we first need to understand that the Fibonacci sequence is recursively defined.
\[
\text{Fibonacci } n=\left \{ 
\begin{array}{cc} 
1, & n = 0 \\ 
1, & n = 1 \\ 
\text{Fibonacci } (n-1) + \text{Fibonacci } (n-2), & n > 1 \\ 
\end{array}
\right. 
\end{array}
{/eq}

To get the remainders when dividing the terms by 8, we look at mod 8 added to the last two remainders. Upon adding, we will see a new cycle, as the remainders reset back on the ninth term instead of the tenth term as $9 \equiv 1, {10} \equiv 1, \ldots$

{{answer}3 <answer></answer>

