Denote spherical coordinates as $(\rho,\theta,\phi),$ and let be $(\rho,\theta,\phi)$ spherical coordinates of said point. Then, from these coordinates we obtain rectangular coordinates as
\begin{align*}
(x, y, z) &= (\rho \sin \theta \cos \phi, \rho \sin \theta \sin \phi, \rho \cos \theta), \hspace{1cm} (A)
\end{align*}
where 
\begin{align*}
\rho^2 &= x^2 + y^2 + z^2 \\
0 &\le \theta \le \pi, \\
0 &\le \phi \le 2 \pi.
\end{align*}
Given rectangular coordinates in $(A),$ we obtain the following piece of Cartesian coordinates:
\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix}x \\ y \\ -z \end{pmatrix} &= -1 \begin{pmatrix}-x \\ -y \\ z \end{pmatrix} \\
&= -1 \begin{pmatrix}\rho \sin \theta \cos \phi \\ \rho \sin \theta \sin \phi \\ \rho \cos \theta \end{pmatrix} \\
&= (-\rho \sin \theta \cos \phi, -\rho \sin \theta \sin \phi, \rho \cos \theta). \hspace{1cm} (B)
\end{align*}
denote by $<\tau>$ the spherical coordinates of $(B).$ Thus,
\begin{align*}
\rho^2 &= (\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2})^2 \\
&= \rho^2 \sin^2 \theta \cos^2 \phi + \rho^2 \sin^2 \theta \sin^2 \phi + \rho^2 \cos^2 \theta \\
&= \rho^2 \sin^2 \theta (\cos^2 \phi + \sin^2 \phi) + \rho^2 \cos^2 \theta \\
&= \rho^2 \sin^2 \theta + \rho^2 \cos^2 \theta \\
&= \rho^2 \sin^2 \theta + \cos^2 \theta \rho^2 \\
&= \rho^2.
\end{align*}
Also, since $x < 0$ in $(B),$ $y < 0,$ and $z > 0,$ we deduce that $\theta + \pi > \pi \implies \pi < \theta + \phi \le \pi + \phi,$ and, thus,
\begin{align*}
0 &\le \phi < \pi + \phi \le \pi \\
&\le \phi < \pi - \theta \implies \pi - \theta < 0.
\end{align*}
On the other hand, since $x = -\rho \sin \phi \cos \theta < 0$ and $\rho > 0,$ $\sin \theta > 0,$ we deduce that $\cos \phi > 0,$ which gives 
\begin{align*}
0 &\le \phi \le \pi \\
&\le 2 \pi - \theta \implies 2 \pi - \theta \ge 0.
\end{align*}
Lastly, since $z = \rho \cos \theta > 0,$ we deduce that $\cos \theta > 0,$ from which $\sin \theta > 0$ and $\cos \phi > 0,$ which implies that $0 < \theta + \phi < 2 \pi,$ and, thus,
\begin{align*}
0 &< \theta + \phi < 2 \pi \\
&< \theta < 2 \pi.
\end{align*}
Therefore the spherical coordinates of $(B)$ are given by $<\tau),$ and for such $<\tau)$ to be correct, we must have $\rho > 0,$ $0 < \theta < 2 \pi,$ and we have the latter found, which gives
